nce her tragic death in 1994, become a focus for many scholars interested in contemporary French philosophy. The first critical collection on her thought to appear in English, Enigmas evaluates Kofman's most important contributions to philosophy, psychoanalytic theory, feminism, and literary theory. These insightful essays range from analyses of Kofman's first book, L'Enfance de l'art (1970), to her last, L'Imposture de la beauté (1995). This unique volume represents the major themes in Kofman's scholarship: literature and aesthetics; philosophy and metaphor; women, feminism, and psychoanalysis; and Jews and German nationalism. Selected essays explore and diagnose Kofman's personal struggles as they are reflected in her writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aGender Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Individual Philosophers.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChanter, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeutscher, Penelope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeutscher, Penelope, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDuroux, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKofman, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamarche, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarge, Duncan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMader, Mary Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNancy, Jean-Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliver, Kelly, econtributor.4ctb